<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="sa0061t"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="sa" href="#sa0061t">SA (VI.A) </a>: <a href="../../ff/fnbs/ssaall.htm#sa0061t"> 061(t)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Breeches Bible 1595: <small>Not cancelled</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="sa0061t"><li>FW 539.02 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/lexrB.htm#sa0061t">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/l39rB.htm#sa0061t">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#sa0061t">MS BL 47484a-055</ms> </li><li>JJA 58:200 <a name="rAd4" href="../../ff/fdra/rda.htm#rBd4">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/rB/rBd4.htm#sa0061t">Draft: III&sect;3B.4</a> </li> </ul><mm class="note">Note: : An issue of the whole Bible appeared in 1560, the so-called <cite>Genevan Bible</cite>, popularly also known as the <cite>Breeches Bible</cite>, from its rendering of Gen. iii. 7, &ldquo;They sewed fig leaves together and made themselves breeeches.&rdquo; The popularity of this version was so great that between 1560 and 1644 at least 1430 editions of it were published, and this in spite of its not being allowed for use in the churches. </mm> </dd></dl>
